# CaptionDB Architecture Contract

## Purpose

This document defines the mandatory architecture for the CaptionDB project.

Every implementation must follow this architecture unless explicitly instructed otherwise by the project owner.

The objective is to build production-quality software for the AMD Developer Hackathon while maintaining a clean, extensible codebase suitable for future open-source development.

This document takes precedence over implementation convenience.

---

# Engineering Philosophy

CaptionDB is NOT a hackathon prototype.

CaptionDB is Version 1 of a production AI platform.

Every architectural decision must prioritize:

- Maintainability
- Readability
- Extensibility
- Performance
- Security
- Testability

Never optimize for writing less code.

Optimize for writing better software.

---

# Core Principles

Always follow:

- SOLID
- DRY
- KISS
- Separation of Concerns
- Dependency Inversion
- Composition over Inheritance
- Explicit over Implicit
- Configuration over Hardcoding

---

# Repository Philosophy

The repository must remain organized.

Separate responsibilities clearly.

Frontend must never contain backend logic.

Backend must never contain frontend logic.

AI logic must never be mixed with API logic.

Business logic must never be mixed with infrastructure.

---

# High Level Architecture

The system consists of the following independent layers:

Frontend

↓

REST API

↓

Application Layer

↓

Pipeline Orchestrator

↓

AI Services

↓

Infrastructure

↓

Storage

Each layer communicates only through well-defined interfaces.

Never bypass layers.

---

# Backend Philosophy

FastAPI is the application backbone.

Do not use FastAPI only for routes.

Use it for:

- dependency injection
- configuration
- application lifecycle
- service orchestration

---

# AI Architecture

Every AI capability must exist behind an abstraction.

Examples:

SceneDetector

OCRService

FireworksClient

PromptManager

CaptionGenerator

JudgeService

MemoryService

Exporter

Never directly call external SDKs throughout the project.

All external services must have dedicated wrapper classes.

---

# Plugin Architecture

Major components must be replaceable.

Examples:

Scene Detection

OCR

Caption Generator

LLM Provider

Embedding Provider

Storage Provider

Export Provider

Changing providers must require minimal code changes.

---

# Dependency Direction

Dependencies always flow inward.

Frontend

→ API

→ Services

→ Interfaces

→ Infrastructure

Never reverse dependency direction.

---

# Configuration Policy

No implementation may hardcode:

API Keys

URLs

Paths

Model IDs

Temperatures

Retry Counts

Timeouts

Frame Counts

Thresholds

Thread Counts

Export Locations

Everything must come from configuration.

---

# Dependency Injection

Services must receive dependencies through constructors or FastAPI dependency injection.

Never instantiate shared services inside business logic.

Avoid global mutable state.

---

# Service Layer

Business logic belongs inside services.

Routes should remain thin.

Routes should:

Validate

↓

Call service

↓

Return response

Nothing more.

---

# API Layer

The API layer must never contain AI logic.

The API layer only:

Validates requests

Calls services

Returns responses

Handles exceptions

---

# Domain Models

Use strongly typed models.

Prefer Pydantic for API schemas.

Prefer dataclasses or domain models where appropriate for internal business logic.

Avoid passing dictionaries between services.

---

# Exception Hierarchy

All custom exceptions inherit from:

CaptionDBException

Examples:

ConfigurationException

ValidationException

SceneDetectionException

OCRException

FireworksException

PipelineException

ExportException

StorageException

Never raise generic Exception unless absolutely necessary.

---

# Logging Philosophy

Never use print().

Every module must use structured logging.

Log:

start

finish

duration

warnings

errors

retry attempts

important decisions

Never log secrets.

Never log API keys.

---

# File Structure

Every folder has one responsibility.

Avoid dumping unrelated modules into one package.

Favor many focused modules over giant files.

---

# Async Philosophy

Use asynchronous programming only when it improves performance or scalability.

Do not convert everything to async unnecessarily.

CPU-bound work should use appropriate execution strategies.

Network operations should use async clients where practical.

---

# Memory Management

Avoid unnecessary object duplication.

Release large objects when no longer needed.

Reuse expensive resources.

Cache expensive computations where beneficial.

---

# Documentation

Every public class

Every public function

Every service

Every API endpoint

must contain documentation.

---

# Testing

Every module must be testable independently.

Avoid hidden dependencies.

Favor dependency injection to simplify testing.

---

# Extensibility

Every architectural decision should consider future versions.

Ask:

Can this component be replaced?

Can another model be used?

Can another OCR engine be added?

Can another storage provider be added?

If the answer is "no", redesign before implementation.

---

# Architecture Decision Process

Before implementing any feature:

Understand the problem.

Identify affected modules.

Review existing architecture.

Avoid duplication.

Prefer extension over modification.

Document important decisions.

Only then implement.

---

# Evidence-Based Engineering

Never invent:

SDK methods

API responses

Library behavior

Framework capabilities

If documentation is unavailable:

Create an interface.

Mark implementation with TODO.

Explain assumptions.

Do not fabricate code.

---

# Self Review

Before completing any implementation verify:

Architecture consistency

No hardcoded values

No duplicated logic

Proper abstraction

Correct dependency direction

Proper exception handling

Logging present

Configuration driven

Documentation updated

Tests planned

If any check fails, revise the implementation before considering it complete.

---

End of Architecture Contract.  
